IRS990.MissionDesc: To protect and improve the quality of life in the Town of Palm Beach by taking proactive stands on civic affairs; informing, educating, and engaging residents on key town issues; working with local government; and encouraging citizen involvement in the community.
IRS990.Desc: Advancement of civic interest in the Town of Palm Beach, and the quality of life therein; devising, considering and advancing the best interests of Palm Beach by conducting educational programs and speaker series.For eight decades, the Palm Beach Civic Association has served as a cornerstone of the community, working tirelessly to protect and improve the quality of life in Palm Beach by taking proactive stands on civic affairs, informing, educating, and engaging residents on key town issues; working with local government; and encouraging citizen involvement in the community. (Continues on Schedule O) The Palm Beach Civic Association comprises numerous and varied committees that collaborate on key issues, ranging from environmental conservation and beautification to fiscal responsibility and healthcare.

SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: The Civic Association is a not-for-profit organization other than a private foundation under Internal Revenue Code Section 501(c)(3) since it is organized and operates for educational purposes. Internal Revenue Code Section 501(a) exempts the Civic Association from income taxes and Internal Revenue Code Section 170(b)(1)(A)(VI) allows donors a deduction for contributions to the Civic Association. The Civic Association evaluates its uncertain tax position in accordance with FASB ASC 740-10, Accounting for Uncertainty in Income Taxes. This pronouncement seeks to reduce the diversity in practice associated with certain aspects of measurement and recognition in accounting for income taxes. It prescribes a recognition threshold and measurement attribute for financial statement recognition and measurement of a tax position that an entity takes or expects to take in a tax return. An entity may only recognize or continue to recognize tax positions that meet a "more likely than not" threshold. The Civic Association assesses its income tax positions based on management's evaluation of the facts, circumstances, and information available at the reporting date. The Civic Association uses the prescribed more likely than not threshold when making its assessment. The Civic Association has not accrued any interest expense or penalties related to tax positions. There are currently no open Federal or State tax years under audit.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Section A, line 4
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: The Organization added term limits for officers. Previous policy - Directors shall be elected by the vote of the general membership at the annual meeting of the general membership of the Civic Association. Directors elected at the annual meeting of the general membership of the Civic Association shall hold office for one-year terms. The Board shall designate annually, 17 of its members to constitute members of the Executive Committee. The Executive Committee serves at the pleasure of the Board and runs the organization on a day-to-day basis. Addition to policy - The Board shall designate annually not less than five of its members to serve on the Executive Committee for a term of three years. There shall be not more than 17 members of the Executive Committee each serving staggered three-year terms with approximately one third of the Executive Committee up for election by the Board each year.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Section A, line 7b
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: Ultimately, all decisions of the governing body (the Executive Committee), are subject to approval by the Board who can vote the executive committee members out of office at the next annual meeting. In addition, all changes to the bylaws are subject to approval by the membership. The Board shall have the power to remove any director, either with or without cause, at any meeting of the Board. The Executive Committee may remove any officer at any time, either with or without cause.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Section B, line 11b
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: A copy of the Form 990 is given to the President, Treasurer and the Audit Committee and/or Audit Committee Chair for their independent review and approval, before the tax return is filed.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Section B, line 12c
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: All conflicts of interest are to be immediately reported to the Governance Committee and the Chairman of the Executive Committee. They are then recorded in the minutes of an executive committee meeting and the committee determines the appropriate action needed to address the conflict. A member who has a conflict shall not participate in any executive committee discussion, or other association committee discussion, in which the subject of the conflict is at issue.
